<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-04-30T12:45:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-04-30T12:45:00-05:00" n="310" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d310">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/4741: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Eberhardt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-04-30T12:00:00-05:45"><hi rend="italic">April 30,
                                        1927—noon</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received 4:25
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>117. Following from Stimson:</p>
                        <p>“New Minister Foreign Affairs of Salvador evidencing persistent desire to
                            intrude into my unofficial negotiations with Sacasa conferees. He seems
                            to be making progress in enlisting other Central American countries,
                            viz. Guatemala and Costa Rica. Sacasa conferees have not yet brought up
                            question but we think that situation contains risk. Can you take steps
                            in Washington to head it off? Stimson”.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Eberhardt</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>